<p>Title: &nbsp;<strong>Electronic, Magnetic and Electrochemical Profile of=
 Transition Metal based&nbsp;Olivine Phosphates</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p>Speaker: <strong>Mr. Ajit Jena</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Chair: Prof. P. N. Santhosh<br>
</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<p>Guide: B. R. K.&nbsp;Nanda<br>
</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p>
<p>Date &amp; Time: 22<sup>nd</sup> June (Wednesday), 3 PM</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Venue: Physics Seminar Hall (# HSB209)</p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center"><strong>Abstract</strong></p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center"><strong><br>
</strong></p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">Using density functional theory and climbin=
g image nudged elastic band methods, we have investigated the electronic st=
ructure and electrochemical profile of pure and doped olivine phosphates Li=
M<sub>1-x</sub> M<sup>&#697;</sup><sub>x</sub>PO<sub>4</sub>,
 M and M<sup>&#697;</sup> being the 3d transition metal elements. We demons=
trate that none of the conventional mechanisms such as Mott-Hubbard, charge=
-transfer, and Slater are strictly applicable to explain the antiferromagne=
tic and insulating (AFI) ground state
 of these systems. Due the substantial symmetry lowering of the metal-oxyge=
n complex, thanks to the presence of PO<sub>4</sub> tetrahedra, the covalen=
t hybridization is nearly absent. This leads the Bloch electrons to behave =
like atomically localized electron
 causing the AFI behaviour in the system. The compounds are classified as w=
eekly coupled Mott insulator. Doped systems tend to have a lower band gap s=
ince the dopant-d states always lie within the band gap of the pure compoun=
d. Analysing the electrochemical
 properties, in regard to LiFePO<sub>4</sub>, we find higher valence electr=
on (HVE) dopants raise the open circuit voltage. The effect of dopants on L=
i<sup>&#43;</sup> ion diffusion is found to be site selective and short ran=
ged. Dopants with lower valence electrons
 repeal the Li<sup>&#43;</sup> ion to facilitate its outward diffusion, whe=
reas HVE dopants attract the Li<sup>&#43;</sup> ion for inward diffusion. T=
hrough interface engineering, we show that metallic ferromagnets can be con=
structed from these AFI phosphates.&nbsp;<strong></strong><br>
</p>
